### Key Concepts and Definitions

| Term                      | Definition                                                                                                           |
|---------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| **Vibe Coding**           | A casual, unstructured workflow where developers describe desired outputs in natural language, iterating by trial and error and fixing AI outputs by feeding back error messages. Highly iterative but chaotic for production use. |
| **Agentic Engineering**   | A disciplined, production-level workflow where AI-generated code is constrained by formal specifications, automated test suites, and continuous integration gates to ensure reliability and scalability. |
| **Context Engineering**   | The core modern skill replacing prompt engineering, focusing on feeding AI a highly structured and carefully balanced set of six context types about the codebase and architecture to guide output. |
| **Harness**               | The non-AI infrastructure around a large language model that includes sandboxes, orchestration logic, observability, and guardrails. It accounts for 90% of an AI agent’s capability, managing and guiding the raw AI model’s output safely and effectively. |
| **Factory Model**         | The new paradigm of software development where developers primarily build and maintain the “factory”—the system that produces code—rather than typing code themselves. |
| **80% Problem**           | The observation that AI can automatically generate roughly 80% of typical software features, mostly boilerplate, while the remaining 20% consists of complex edge cases requiring human expertise. |

